<section class="section section--alt" id="recon-why-fails-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">A systemic failure, not a one-time error.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>There&rsquo;s a difference between a reconciliation that fails <em>once</em> and one that fails <em>over and over</em>. A one-time failure has a single cause &mdash; a missing transaction, a typo &mdash; and once you find it, it stays fixed. A systemic failure comes back: the ending balance won&rsquo;t tie this month, then it won&rsquo;t tie next month, prior periods quietly reopen, and the adjustment account keeps growing. The error isn&rsquo;t a transaction; it&rsquo;s something in the <em>process</em> that re-introduces the same fault every period.</p>
      <p>That distinction matters because it changes the fix. You can&rsquo;t patch a systemic failure with one more adjustment &mdash; that&rsquo;s usually what made it worse. The causes below are ranked by how often they&rsquo;re the true root, and the process fixes that follow address them in the same order. This page is the educational, root-cause view. If reconciliation is broken <em>right now</em> and you need to triage it fast, see <a href="/quickbooks/help/reconciliation-broken/">reconciliation is broken</a>; if you&rsquo;re chasing one specific difference, see <a href="/quickbooks/reconciliation/discrepancies/">how to diagnose a reconciliation discrepancy</a>. Here we cover <em>why it keeps happening</em> &mdash; and how to make it stop.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

